PROMPT spark_vs_mapreduce_comparison
WITH BUDGET 8000 tokens
USING MODEL "claude-sonnet-4-5"

SELECT
    system_role("You are a distributed computing expert specializing in big data processing frameworks, Apache Spark architecture, and Hadoop ecosystem technologies with deep knowledge of execution models and performance optimization.")

GENERATE
    compare_execution_models("Explain Apache Spark and how its execution model fundamentally differs from Hadoop MapReduce, covering: Apache Spark definition as a unified analytics engine for large-scale data processing that provides high-level APIs in Java, Scala, Python, and R, along with an optimized engine that supports general computation graphs for data analysis, originally developed at UC Berkeley's AMPLab to address MapReduce limitations, Spark's core architecture built around Resilient Distributed Datasets (RDDs) as immutable distributed collections of objects that can be cached in memory across cluster nodes, enabling fault tolerance through lineage information rather than replication, execution model differences where MapReduce follows a rigid two-phase batch processing model with map and reduce stages that write intermediate results to disk after each stage, while Spark uses a Directed Acyclic Graph (DAG) execution engine that can chain multiple operations together in memory without intermediate disk writes, performance characteristics showing MapReduce's slower performance due to frequent disk I/O operations and the overhead of starting new JVM processes for each task, versus Spark's significantly faster processing through in-memory computing, lazy evaluation that optimizes entire computation pipelines, and reuse of worker processes, memory management where MapReduce relies heavily on disk-based storage with limited memory usage, while Spark leverages cluster memory for caching frequently accessed data and intermediate results, reducing I/O bottlenecks and enabling iterative algorithms to run efficiently, programming model differences with MapReduce requiring developers to think in terms of map and reduce functions with complex multi-stage jobs requiring chaining multiple MapReduce programs, while Spark provides high-level APIs with transformations and actions that allow more natural expression of complex data processing logic, fault tolerance mechanisms where MapReduce achieves fault tolerance by writing intermediate data to HDFS and restarting failed tasks from checkpoints, versus Spark's RDD lineage that reconstructs lost data by recomputing from the original source using the recorded transformation sequence, data processing capabilities showing MapReduce's limitation to batch processing with high latency, while Spark supports multiple workloads including batch processing, real-time stream processing through Spark Streaming and Structured Streaming, interactive SQL queries via Spark SQL, machine learning through MLlib, and graph processing with GraphX, resource utilization differences where MapReduce launches separate JVM processes for each task leading to overhead and slower startup times, while Spark uses long-running executor processes that can handle multiple tasks, reducing overhead and improving resource efficiency, optimization features including Spark's Catalyst optimizer for SQL queries that performs rule-based and cost-based optimizations, automatic broadcast joins for small tables, and columnar storage formats like Parquet integration, versus MapReduce's limited optimization capabilities, ease of development where MapReduce requires significant boilerplate code and deep understanding of the framework internals, while Spark provides intuitive APIs that abstract complex distributed computing concepts, practical use case scenarios where MapReduce is suitable for simple batch processing jobs with predictable resource requirements and when disk-based processing is acceptable, while Spark excels for iterative algorithms, real-time analytics, interactive data exploration, machine learning pipelines, and complex ETL processes, deployment considerations including Spark's ability to run on various cluster managers like Hadoop YARN, Apache Mesos, and Kubernetes, versus MapReduce's tight coupling with Hadoop YARN, and performance benchmarks showing Spark can be 10-100x faster than MapReduce for iterative algorithms and up to 3x faster for batch processing workloads due to memory optimization and reduced disk I/O.")
WITH OUTPUT BUDGET 4000 tokens, TEMPERATURE 0.2, FORMAT markdown;